Based in Beaverton, OR, Nike is a designer, marketer and distributor of athletic footwear, apparel, equipment and accessories for a wide variety of sports and fitness activities. 

Wholly owned Nike subsidiaries include Converse Inc., which designs, markets and distributes athletic footwear, apparel and accessories; and Hurley International LLC, which designs, markets and distributes action sports and youth lifestyle footwear, apparel and accessories.

The company also has distribution centers and other offices in Wilsonville, OR, St. Louis, MO, and Memphis, TN.

2013 and Earlier:
The IT department of Nike, Inc. is primarily centralized in Beaverton, OR. 

The CIO oversees several executives of Nike's business line in IT functions including Retail operations and Apparel. The CIO also manages several Vice Presidents and Directors who oversee IT functions on a global scale in areas including Global IT Security, Global Distribution Systems and Global IT Operations.

Nike's IT department works in close collaboration with its business divisions and therefore employs staff who specialize in areas including Business Intelligence Strategy, eBusiness, Big Data, and Business Intelligence Tools Configuration. On a lower level, Managers are responsible for a variety of IT functions in areas including Disaster Recovery, Storage, Applications Development, Compliance, Infrastructure, and Network Architecture.

Nike views its Global Electronic Commerce as a major expansion opportunity. Therefore, the company is focusing on ways to improve that division. Nike.com is their primary Internet presence, but they also maintain Nike.net for internal use and for Nike retailers. 

Nike and Affiliated Computer Services (ACS) has a five-year contract extension through 2013. ACS provides Nike with a suite of information technology outsourcing services, including global data center services, network and security services, and mainframe and midrange messaging. Nike has also contracted ACS to use its ACSM management system to integrate differing software, networking, and server monitoring into a single client delivery platform.  

The budget is typically finalized in Q3.

IT Intelligence Snippets 
2013:
• Between 30-50% of IT staff is dedicated to the sustenance of its ERP platform, and between 30-50% of ERP support is outsourced to a third party. 
• Expects around 14 releases/updates a year with its current ERP solution. 
• The budget is typically finalized in Q3.
• Currently has a bring your own device (BYOD) program in place. The program allows iOS and BlackBerry devices to sign into the company's network. The company is looking to expand in the future to include Android devices. The company also is exploring Big Data solutions but nothing in this area is imminent.

2012: 
• Evaluating and hoping to deploy Sybase in the near future
• Investing in warehouse deployment, SQL deployment in outlying offices, and Hadoop installed solutions.





